    "finalTextPreview": "Vision established and recorded. The project is now clearly defined with scope boundaries, tone, and concrete deliverables — ready for the build team to execute against this brief.",
    "brief": "WHAT: A browser-based personal finance dashboard web application that enables users to record financial transactions, view monthly spending summaries via charts, and manage per-category budgets with real-time tracking against actuals. The app is self-contained (client-server architecture) with local-first data persistence for privacy.\n\nTONE & SCOPE: Modern, minimalist, and trustworthy — prioritizing clarity and ease of use over flashy features. \n\nIN SCOPE: \n- Transaction logging (amount, date, category, description)\n- Computed monthly summaries aggregating by category and total\n- Interactive charts/visualizations for spending trends\n- Filterable transaction list (date range, category filters)\n- Per-category budget setting with limit tracking\n- Budget progress indicators (percent used vs. allowed)\n\nOUT OF SCOPE: \n- Bank account aggregation/API integration\n- Investment or savings tracking\n- Tax planning tools\n- Multi-user collaboration features\n- Mobile app wrapper\n- Cloud-based data backup\n\nDELIVERABLES — What \"done\" looks like:\n1) Backend/data module: RESTful endpoints (or internal service) for CRUD on transactions and budgets, monthly summary aggregation logic, data persistence layer with local storage or embedded database.\n2) Frontend dashboard: Main landing page with navigation between modules; spending charts (pie/bar line); filterable transaction list with sorting/export.\n3) Budgets module: Interface to create/edit/delete category budgets with limits; visual indicators showing budget health (e.g., circular progress, color-coded status).\n4) Authentication or session handling (browser-based, no external auth required).\n5) Data migration/reset functionality for users.\n\nSuccess criteria: A user can log a transaction within 10 seconds, view monthly spending breakdown via chart with <2 second load time, set up 5 budget categories and see live alerts when approaching limits, and export the full transaction history as CSV."
